      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1183">
               <p>Mary Forrest (of <placeName>Minehead, Somerset</placeName>) married <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1185.xml"/>Robert Jones</persName> (<date from="1706"
                     to="1742">1706–42</date>) of Fonmon Castle near <placeName>Cardiff,
                     Glamorganshire</placeName> in <date when="1732">1732</date>. <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1185.xml"/>Robert</persName> came under the influence
                  of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0950.xml"/>Howell Harris</persName> in
                     <date when="1741">1741</date>, became a Methodist, and a warm friend of
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> and
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName>. <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> wrote an extended elegy on the
                  death of Mary&apos;s husband in <date when="1742-06">June 1742</date>, and both
                  brothers kept up a close relationship with her and her five surviving children:
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1184.xml"/>Mary</persName>
                  (&apos;Molly&apos; <date from="1733" to="1781">1733–81</date>), <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1186.xml"/>Robert</persName> (&apos;Robin&apos; c.
                     <date from="1734" to="1793">1734–93</date>), <persName>Catherine</persName>
                  (&apos;Kitty&apos; <date from="1735" to="1768">1735–68</date>),
                     <persName>Charlotte</persName> (<date from="1737" to="1816">1737–1816</date>),
                  and <persName>Diana</persName> (<date from="1738" to="1822">1738–1822</date>).
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> made nearly
                  annual visits to Fonmon Castle, while Mary was often in the
                     <placeName>Bristol</placeName> area, where <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> and <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2191.xml"/>Sarah</persName> could encourage her. See
                  George T. Clark, <hi rend="italic">Limbus Patrum Morganiae et Glamorganiae</hi>
                     (<placeName>London</placeName>: Wyman, <date when="1886">1886</date>), 216; and
                  Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 185.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
